<AbstractNarration>The proposed project will consider the best possible role of randomized field trials in&lt;br/&gt;research projects in STEM education research projects. Two workshops and one&lt;br/&gt;Summative Convocation will direct the attention of scholars to addressing the benefits of&lt;br/&gt;randomization for large- and small-scale STEM education research, impediments to&lt;br/&gt;carrying out research designs that use randomization, and important ways in which&lt;br/&gt;randomization could be adapted to real-world logistical constraints of schools as well as&lt;br/&gt;local needs. The project's intellectual merits arise from the intended value of the&lt;br/&gt;workshops and Convocation for clarifying research designs that best yield actionable&lt;br/&gt;knowledge in STEM education. Broader impacts are foreseeable through clarifying&lt;br/&gt;research processes that are most compatible with the interests of school-age learners.&lt;br/&gt;Through the two workshops and a Summative Convocation, the distinctions, issues, and&lt;br/&gt;debates about randomization in STEM education can be clarified and disseminated to&lt;br/&gt;researchers and to the professional staff of funding agencies.&lt;br/&gt;</AbstractNarration>
